<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF616ADEF82293131883BDC3" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF616ADEF82293131883BDC3" blockId="154.[2012,2608,1275,1703]" lastBlockId="154.[1391,2604,1707,3238]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF616ADEF82293131694BE59" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[2014,2196,1354,1387]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="suilla">Munrina suilla</taxonomicName>
appears to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF616ADEF7FE9328169ABEA0" box="[2050,2202,1393,1426]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="154" pageNumber="916" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="walstoni">M. walstoni</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF616ADEF75693281736BEA0" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1908" box="[2218,2358,1393,1426]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="florium">M. florium</taxonomicName>
(perhaps conspecific), and 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF616ADEF77E93C016FEBE88" authorityName="Goodwin" authorityYear="1958" box="[2178,2302,1433,1466]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Rhogeessa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aenea">M. aenea</taxonomicName>
and possibly 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF616ADEF62C93C0164EBED3" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="annamitica">M. annamitica</taxonomicName>
based on limited genetic data. 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF616ADEF82293B11695BD3B" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[2014,2197,1512,1545]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="suilla">Murina suilla</taxonomicName>
might represent at least two species that are possibly sympatric on Java, but genetic and morphological data are needed to confirm this. Specimens from the 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFF616ADEF7EB90DF16B5BD95" box="[2071,2229,1670,1703]" name="Philippines" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Philippines</collectingCountry>
were originally identified as 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF616ADEFA6090F2183FBDFE" baseAuthorityName="Scully" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[1436,1599,1707,1740]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="154" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tubinaris">M. tubinaris</taxonomicName>
but are best included under M. 
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF616ADEF7F390F21655BDFE" baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[2063,2133,1707,1740]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="suilla">suilla</taxonomicName>
without further testing. Two subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF616ADEFA8A90A11713B335" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" type="synonymic_list">
<caption id="90EB6676FF616ADEFA8A90A11713B335" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6398602" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6398602" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6398602/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" targetBox="[1397,1988,1282,1696]" targetPageId="154">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF616ADEFA8A90A1176FBC58" blockId="154.[1391,2604,1707,3238]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF616ADEFA8A90A11906BC2B" bold="true" box="[1398,1798,1784,1817]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Subspecies and Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF616ADEFA8B917B18F7BC71" authority="Temminck, 1840" authorityName="Temminck" authorityYear="1840" box="[1399,1783,1826,1859]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="suilla" subSpecies="swilla">M.s.swillaTemminck,1840—MalayPeninsula(includingLangkawiI),Borneo,Suma-tra,Java,andthePhilippines(Luzon,Cebu,Mindanao,andPalawanIs).</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF616ADEFA8B912D165ABCA3" blockId="154.[1391,2604,1707,3238]" box="[1399,2138,1908,1937]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF616ADEFA8B912D1905BCA3" authority="Thomas, 1923" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1923" box="[1399,1797,1908,1937]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="suilla" subSpecies="canescens">M. s. canescens Thomas, 1923</taxonomicName>
— Nias I, off W 
<collectingRegion id="0650F81CFF616ADEF823912D1656BCA3" box="[2015,2134,1908,1937]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF616ADEFA8891C11713B335" blockId="154.[1391,2604,1707,3238]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">
Apparently also in C Sulawesi, Peleng I, and New 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFF616ADEF7AF91C116B9BC8B" box="[2131,2233,1944,1977]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Guinea</collectingCountry>
because these specimens are similar to this speciesin size, although they were originally identified as the 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFF616ADEF62991E61429BCD2" box="[2517,2601,1983,2016]" name="Indonesia" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Flores</collectingCountry>
Tube-nosed Bat (
<taxonomicName id="03944D7DFF616ADEF99A91BF18FAB335" authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1908" box="[1638,1786,2022,2055]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="florium">M. florium</taxonomicName>
). These records are not mapped here.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF616ADEFA899E4E17CAB2D0" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" type="description">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF616ADEFA899E4E17CAB2D0" blockId="154.[1391,2604,1707,3238]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF616ADEFA899E4E186FB302" bold="true" box="[1397,1647,2071,2096]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 33-2-62- 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF616ADEF85D9E4E19F1B302" box="[1953,2033,2071,2096]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
, tail 22-5-35- 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF616ADEF74A9E4E170CB302" box="[2230,2316,2071,2096]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
, ear 11-1-14- 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF616ADEF6369E4E1422B302" box="[2506,2594,2071,2096]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
, hindfoot 5-8-8- 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF616ADEF9B29E6F18A5B365" box="[1614,1701,2102,2135]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
, forearm 29-3-33- 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF616ADEF8559E6F19FFB365" box="[1961,2047,2102,2135]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
; weight 2-5-5- 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF616ADEF7379E6F16FBB365" box="[2251,2299,2102,2135]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="5.0" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" unit="g" value="5.0">5 g</quantity>
. Fursilky. Dorsal pelage is orangish brown (hairs having brown bases and orange reddish brown tips); venter is garish brown or sometimes dark brown. Dorsal pelage extends sparsely onto wings, uropatagium, thumbs, and feet. Face is sparsely haired except for long protuberant naked nostrils. Ears are short, broad, and rounded, with smoothly convex anterior margins, distinct notch on posterior margins, and broadly roundedtips; tragus is long and narrow and tapers toward pointed tips. Wing attaches near base of claw on first toe. Skull has relatively inflated rostrum and domed braincase; I2 is anterior to I%; C' is taller than P*; P* is about one-half the height of P*; mesostyles of M' and M2 are well developed, with convex labial surface; and talonids of M, and M, are larger than their respective trigonids. Chromosomal complement has 2n = 44 and FN = 58.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF616ADEFA8E9FB0181DB14F" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF616ADEFA8E9FB0181DB14F" blockId="154.[1391,2604,1707,3238]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF616ADEFA8E9FB01BE1B138" bold="true" box="[1394,1505,2537,2570]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Habitat.</emphasis>
Disturbed and undisturbed mixed deciduous, semi-evergreen, lowland dipterocarp forests; primary lowland evergreen forests; and some heavily disturbed habitats, including banana plantations and human cities, from sea level up to elevations of c. 
<quantity id="036C9B1BFF616ADEFA559C391819B14F" box="[1449,1561,2656,2685]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.54" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" unit="mm" value="1540.0">1540 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF616ADEFA8D9CDE1926B1FF" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF616ADEFA8D9CDE1926B1FF" blockId="154.[1391,2604,1707,3238]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF616ADEFA8D9CDE187AB19A" bold="true" box="[1393,1658,2695,2728]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
The Brown Tube-nosed Bat forages for insects in plantations and areas with clustered vegetation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF616ADEFA8D9C8C1BF2B070" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" type="breeding">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF616ADEFA8D9C8C1BF2B070" blockId="154.[1391,2604,1707,3238]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF616ADEFA8D9C8C1BF7B1C4" bold="true" box="[1393,1527,2773,2806]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Breeding.</emphasis>
Female Brown Tube-nosed Bats captured in February and May were lactating in 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFF616ADEFA2F9D581855B02C" box="[1491,1621,2817,2846]" name="Thailand" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Thailand</collectingCountry>
. They generally give birth to one young, but twins are occasionally reported.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF616ADEFA939D15164BB0D1" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" type="activity">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF616ADEFA939D15164BB0D1" blockId="154.[1391,2604,1707,3238]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF616ADEFA939D15185FB05F" bold="true" box="[1391,1631,2892,2925]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
The Brown Tube-nosed Bats roost in foliage. Calls are steep FM sweeps, with average start frequency of 171 kHz (146-246 kHz), end frequency of 58-4 kHz (48-85 kHz), peak frequency of 97 kHz (74-1-146-1 kHz), and duration of 2-7 milliseconds (1-7—4-9 milliseconds) in 
<collectingCountry id="BC83766EFF616ADEF83A9D9F1648B0D1" box="[1990,2120,3014,3043]" name="Thailand" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Thailand</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF616ADEFA939DB0171BB738" box="[1391,2331,3049,3082]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF616ADEFA939DB0171BB738" blockId="154.[1391,2604,1707,3238]" box="[1391,2331,3049,3082]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF616ADEFA939DB0162CB738" bold="true" box="[1391,2092,3049,3082]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FF616ADEFA8C9A4C1679B794" pageId="154" pageNumber="915" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFF616ADEFA8C9A4C1679B794" blockId="154.[1391,2604,1707,3238]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFF616ADEFA8C9A4C18CAB700" bold="true" box="[1392,1738,3093,3122]" pageId="154" pageNumber="915">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List. The Brown Tube-nosed Bat is common throughout much ofits wide distribution and does not seem to face any major threats. In Borneo, it reportedly increased in abundance after logging, suggesting it is adaptable to disturbed habitats.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
